# Alpine.js Patterns

## Job status values

The frontend `steps` array and the backend `on_status` callback must use **exactly** these values in order:

```
queued → fetching_isbn → searching → downloading → sending → done
```

On failure: `error`. Any change to this sequence requires updating **both** `download_flow.py` and `static/index.html`.

## Alpine.js reactivity — use proxied references

After pushing to an Alpine reactive array, use the array index to get the proxied object. Holding onto the original object reference bypasses reactivity:

```javascript
// ✅ Correct — mutate via the proxied reference
this.activeJobs.unshift(jobObj);
const job = this.activeJobs[0];  // Alpine-proxied reference
job.status = 'downloading';      // Alpine detects the change

// ❌ Wrong — jobObj is not proxied, Alpine won't detect mutations
this.activeJobs.unshift(jobObj);
jobObj.status = 'downloading';   // invisible to Alpine
```

## Error parsing helper

The frontend uses `parseError(res)` to handle API errors gracefully:

```javascript
async function parseError(res) {
    try {
        const data = await res.json();
        return data.detail || JSON.stringify(data);
    } catch {
        return await res.text();
    }
}
```

## Polling interval

Job status is polled every **2 seconds** via `setInterval` against `GET /jobs/{job_id}`.
